issue.body:
### What version of Go are you using (`go version`)? 
$ go version
go version go1.20.5 linux/amd64
### Does this issue reproduce with the latest release? Yes. ### What operating system and processor architecture are you using (`go env`)?
go env Output
$ go env

GOBIN=""

GOROOT="/usr/local/go"
GOSUMDB="[sum.golang.org](http://sum.golang.org/)"
GOTMPDIR=""
GOTOOLDIR="/usr/local/go/pkg/tool/linux_amd64"
GOVCS=""
GOVERSION="go1.20.5"
GCCGO="gccgo"
GOAMD64="v1"
AR="ar"
CC="gcc"
CXX="g++"
CGO_ENABLED="1"
GOMOD="/home/slim/pub/src/frankenphp/go.mod"
GOWORK=""
CGO_CFLAGS="-O2 -g"
CGO_CPPFLAGS=""
CGO_CXXFLAGS="-O2 -g"
CGO_FFLAGS="-O2 -g"
CGO_LDFLAGS="-O2 -g"
PKG_CONFIG="pkg-config"
GOGCCFLAGS="-fPIC -m64 -pthread -Wl,--no-gc-sections -fmessage-length=0 -fdebug-prefix-map=/tmp/go-build3097512463=/tmp/go-build -gno-record-gcc-switches"
### What did you do? [FrankenPHP](https://frankenphp.dev) is a Go module that embeds the PHP executor in Go programs such as the Caddy web server, and handles HTTP requests received by "net/http" with PHP scripts executed directly in the Go process, similarly to Apache mod_php. To do so PHP is compiled as a C library and executed using cgo. Under certain conditions, if the script uses [PHP fibers](https://www.php.net/manual/en/language.fibers.php), the program crashes with the message "fatal: morestack on g0" (see backtraces and reproducer below). PHP Fibers do low-level stack manipulation and are likely badly interacting Go and cgo own stack management. Under the hood, PHP Fibers can use the [boost.context library](https://github.com/boostorg/context) (by default) or `ucontext.h` (if PHP is compiled with `--disable-fiber-asm`). The problem occurs with both implementations. Fibers code is in https://github.com/php/php-src/blob/master/Zend/zend_fibers.c. The problem seems to only randomly occur and only on Linux with x86 processors (we're not able to reproduce this on Mac or on ARM). The problem seems to occur when the C code executed in a PHP Fiber (with its own stack) calls a Go function using cgo. We currently have no idea if it's a problem in Go, in PHP, or "just" a bad interaction of their respective stack management systems. ### What did you expect to see? No error. ### What did you see instead? `fatal: morestack on g0` Here are some stack traces collected by @slim with GDB: ``` (gdb) backtrace #0 Â 0x0000000000470106 in ?? A reproducer as well as some extra investigation are available in this PR: https://github.com/dunglas/frankenphp/pull/171 The problem can be reproduced locally [by compiling PHP with the appropriate flags needed by FrankenPHP](https://github.com/dunglas/frankenphp/blob/main/docs/compile.md), checking out the `fibers` branch of FrankenPHP and running `go test -run Fiber`.

Refactor: Memindahkan logika validasi atasan ke model User

Memindahkan logika bisnis untuk memvalidasi peran atasan dari `UserController` ke metode statis baru `getValidSupervisorRolesFor` di model `User`. Ini membersihkan controller dan menempatkan aturan bisnis yang terkait dengan entitas User di dalam modelnya sendiri, sesuai dengan praktik terbaik.

- Menghapus array privat `$VALID_PARENT_ROLES` dari `UserController`.
- Menambahkan metode statis `getValidSupervisorRolesFor` ke `User.php`.
- Memperbarui metode `store` dan `update` di `UserController` untuk menggunakan metode statis yang baru.

Refactor: Menyederhanakan form pembuatan pengguna admin

Menyesuaikan alur pembuatan pengguna di panel admin agar konsisten dengan alur registrasi publik yang baru.

- Form 'Tambah/Edit Pengguna' sekarang hanya mewajibkan field dasar: Nama, NIP, Tanggal Lahir, Email, dan Password.
- Pemilihan `jabatan_id` sekarang bersifat opsional saat admin membuat pengguna.
- Jika jabatan tidak dipilih, pengguna akan dibuat tanpa unit dan dengan peran default. Middleware `CheckProfileIsComplete` yang ada akan mengarahkan pengguna ini untuk melengkapi profil mereka saat login pertama.
- Aturan validasi di `UserController` telah diperbarui untuk mencerminkan perubahan ini.

commits.message:
feat(relay): Support DRV_MODE with gVNIC driver

This updates our eBPF module to use DRV_MODE for less CPU overhead and
better performance for all same-stack TURN relaying.

Notably, gVNIV does not seem to support the `bpf_xdp_adjust_head`
helper, so unfortunately we need to extend / shrink the packet tail
and move the payload instead.

Comprehensive benchmarks have not been performed, but early results
show that we can saturate about 1 Gbps per E2 core on GCP:

```
[SUM]   0.00-30.04  sec  3.16 GBytes   904 Mbits/sec  12088             sender
[SUM]   0.00-30.00  sec  3.12 GBytes   894 Mbits/sec                  receiver
```

This is with 64 TCP streams. More streams will better utilize all
available RX queues, and lead to better performance.

Related: https://github.com/firezone/firezone/issues/10138

Add isolation test for TOAST value reuse during CLUSTER

This test exercises the corner case in toast_save_datum() where CLUSTER
operations encounter duplicated TOAST references, reusing the existing
TOAST data instead of creating redundant copies.

During table rewrites like CLUSTER, both live and recently-dead versions
of a row may reference the same TOAST value.  When copying the second or
later version of such a row, the system checks if a TOAST value already
exists in the new TOAST table using toastrel_valueid_exists().  If
found, toast_save_datum() sets data_todo = 0 so as redundant data is not
stored, ensuring only one copy of the TOAST value exists in the new
table.

The test relies on a combination of UPDATE, CLUSTER, and checks of the
TOAST values used before and after the relation rewrite, to make sure
that the same values are reused across the rewrite.

This is a continuation of 69f75d671475 to make sure that this corner
case keeps working should we mess with this area of the code.

Author: Nikhil Kumar Veldanda <veldanda.nikhilkumar17@gmail.com>
Discussion: https://postgr.es/m/CAFAfj_E+kw5P713S8_jZyVgQAGVFfzFiTUJPrgo-TTtJJoazQw@mail.gmail.com

Author: Etsuro Fujita <etsuro.fujita@gmail.com>
Reviewed-by: Dean Rasheed <dean.a.rasheed@gmail.com>
Discussion: https://postgr.es/m/CAPmGK14NF5CcdCmTZpxrvpvBiT0y4EqKikW1r_wAu1CEHeOmUA%40mail.gmail.com
Backpatch-through: 14

Introduce feature to start WAL receiver eagerly

This commit introduces a new GUC wal_receiver_start_condition which can
enable the standby to start it's WAL receiver at an earlier stage. The
GUC will default to starting the WAL receiver after WAL from archives
and pg_wal have been exhausted, designated by the value 'exhaust'.
The value of 'startup' indicates that the WAL receiver will be started
immediately on standby startup. Finally, the value of 'consistency'
indicates that the server will start after the standby has replayed up
to the consistency point.

If 'startup' or 'consistency' is specified, the starting point for the
WAL receiver will always be the end of all locally available WAL in
pg_wal. The end is determined by finding the latest WAL segment in
pg_wal and then iterating to the earliest segment. The iteration is
terminated as soon as a valid WAL segment is found. Streaming can then
commence from the start of that segment.

Archiving from the restore command does not holds the control lock
and enabling XLogCtl->InstallXLogFileSegmentActive for wal reciever early start
will create a race condition with the checkpointer process as fixed in cc2c7d65fc27e877c9f407587b0b92d46cd6dd16.
Hence skipping early start of the wal receiver in case of archive recovery.

Co-authors: Sunil S<sunilfeb26@gmail.com>, Soumyadeep Chakraborty <soumyadeep2007@gmail.com>, Ashwin Agrawal, Asim Praveen, Wu Hao, Konstantin Knizhnik
Discussion:https://www.postgresql.org/message-id/flat/CANXE4Tc3FNvZ_xAimempJWv_RH9pCvsZH7Yq93o1VuNLjUT-mQ%40mail.gmail.com

Test WAL receiver early start upon reaching consistency

This test ensures that when a standby reaches consistency,
the WAL receiver starts immediately and begins streaming using the latest valid
 WAL segment already available on disk.
This behavior minimizes delay and avoids waiting for WAL file once all the
locally available WAL file is restored and helps in providing `HIGH AVAILABILITY`
incase of Primary crash/failure.

More it helps quicker recovery when `recovery_min_apply_delay` in large and saves
Primary from running out of space.

Co-authors: Sunil S<sunilfeb26@gmail.com>, Soumyadeep Chakraborty <soumyadeep2007@gmail.com>, Ashwin Agrawal, Asim Praveen, Wu Hao, Konstantin Knizhnik
Discussion: https://www.postgresql.org/message-id/flat/CANXE4Tc3FNvZ_xAimempJWv_RH9pCvsZH7Yq93o1VuNLjUT-mQ%40mail.gmail.com

Test archive recovery takes precedence over streaming

Since archive recovery is typically faster and more efficient than streaming,
initiating the WAL receiver earlyâ€”before attempting recovery from archived WAL
filesâ€”is not ideal.
Furthermore, determining the correct starting point for streaming by examining
the last valid WAL segment restored from the archive adds complexity and potential risk.

Therefore, even when the configuration parameter wal_receiver_start_at is set to consistency,
archive recovery should take precedence, and the WAL receiver should only be
started after archive recovery is exhausted or deemed unavailable.

Co-authors: Sunil S<sunilfeb26@gmail.com>, Soumyadeep Chakraborty <soumyadeep2007@gmail.com>, Ashwin Agrawal, Asim Praveen, Wu Hao, Konstantin Knizhnik
Discussion: https://www.postgresql.org/message-id/flat/CANXE4Tc3FNvZ_xAimempJWv_RH9pCvsZH7Yq93o1VuNLjUT-mQ%40mail.gmail.com

pull_request.title: Add Support for Multi-Resource Refresh Tokens (MRRT)
pull_request.body:
<!-- By submitting a PR to this repository, you agree to the terms within the [Auth0 Code of Conduct](https://github.com/auth0/open-source-template/blob/master/CODE-OF-CONDUCT.md). Please see the [contributing guidelines](https://github.com/auth0/.github/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md) for how to create and submit a high-quality PR for this repo. -->

### Changes

The aim of this PR, is to add the possibility to refresh tokens using MRRT functionality. In the `get` method from `cache-manager`, now we can find a RT to refresh a different audience from the ones that are already saved in the cache, letting the user change between audiences.

The user can now decide whether to use MRRT in their requests. If they want to enable it, useMrrt needs to be sent as an option when configuring `Auth0Client`.

To know more about MRRT and how to configure it visit: 
- [Multi-Resource Refresh Token](https://auth0.com/docs/secure/tokens/refresh-tokens/multi-resource-refresh-token)
- [Configure and Implement MRRT](https://auth0.com/docs/secure/tokens/refresh-tokens/multi-resource-refresh-token/configure-and-implement-multi-resource-refresh-token)

### References

<!--
Please include relevant links supporting this change such as a:

- support ticket
- community post
- StackOverflow post
- support forum thread

Please note any links that are not publicly accessible.
-->

### Testing

Manual:

To test it you will need to firstly follow the configuration [guide](https://auth0.com/docs/secure/tokens/refresh-tokens/multi-resource-refresh-token/configure-and-implement-multi-resource-refresh-token), and create two APIs in the dashboard. For both cache locations (`memory`|`localstorage`), try:

1. Initialize a new Auth0 Client with `useMRRT` to `true`, and with this configuration:
`await createAuth0Client({
  domain: '<AUTH0_DOMAIN>',
  clientId: '<AUTH0_CLIENT_ID>',
  useRefreshTokens: true,
  useRefreshTokensFallback: true,
  useMrrt: true,
  authorizationParams: {
    redirect_uri: '<MY_CALLBACK_URL>'
  }`
2. Login to the application with your preferred login method and use `getTokenSilently` to request an access_token for the API_1.
3. After the `access_token` + `refresh_token` from API_1 has been stored, use again `getTokenSilenty` to request an `access_token` for API_2 this time. Internally it will use `refresh_token` from API_1 to do the refresh.

Automated:
Unit tests have been added in:
- `__tests__/cache/cache-manager.test.ts`. Checks that the `refresh_token` from the previous stored audience is returned for the second audience.
- `__tests__/token.worker.test.ts`. Checks that the `refresh_token` obtained from the server for the first audience, is stored as `latest_refresh_token` on worker memory, and is used to do a refresh request for the second audience.

- [x] This change adds unit test coverage
- [x] This change adds integration test coverage
- [x] This change has been tested on the latest version of the platform/language

### Checklist

- [x] I have read the [Auth0 general contribution guidelines](https://github.com/auth0/open-source-template/blob/master/GENERAL-CONTRIBUTING.md)
- [x] I have read the [Auth0 Code of Conduct](https://github.com/auth0/open-source-template/blob/master/CODE-OF-CONDUCT.md)
- [x] All code quality tools/guidelines have been run/followed

pull_request.title: Create .NET 8 Fluent Garmin Library with FIT SDK Integration and Enhanced Repeat Structure Support
pull_request.body:
This PR implements a complete .NET 8 library that provides a fluent wrapper around Garmin's FIT SDK for creating workout files with proper repeat structure support. The library enables developers to easily generate Garmin-compatible workout files using an intuitive, builder-pattern API that follows Garmin's recommended patterns for intervals.

## Key Features

**Fluent API Design**: The library provides an easy-to-use builder pattern for creating workouts with comprehensive examples:

```csharp
// Basic workout pattern
var workout = new WorkoutBuilder()
    .Name("Morning Run")
    .Sport(Sport.Running)
    .WarmUp(10, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)
    .AddTimeStep("Main Set", 20, 4, TargetType.HeartRate)
    .CoolDown(5, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)
    .Build();

// Interval workout with repeat structure using option objects
var intervalOptions = new IntervalOptions 
{
    DurationType = DurationType.Distance,
    Value = 400,
    Zone = 4,
    TargetType = TargetType.Speed
};

var recoveryOptions = new RecoveryOptions
{
    DurationType = DurationType.Time,
    Value = 120,
    TargetType = TargetType.Open
};

var intervals = new WorkoutBuilder()
    .Name("Track Intervals")
    .Sport(Sport.Running)
    .WarmUp(10, 1)
    .AddIntervals("5x400m", 5, intervalOptions, recoveryOptions)
    .CoolDown(10, 1)
    .Build();
```

**Enhanced Method Naming**: Clear distinction between different types of workout steps:
- `AddTimeStep()` and `AddDistanceStep()` for individual workout segments (easy runs, tempo efforts, etc.)
- `AddIntervals()` for structured interval training with repeat patterns
- `AddRepeat()` for custom repeat structures with child steps

**Explicit Parameter Structure**: The `AddIntervals()` method requires explicit option objects for improved code clarity:
- Uses `IntervalOptions` and `RecoveryOptions` parameter objects that must be created and passed in
- Removes convenience overloads that built options internally for better API explicitness

**Proper Repeat Structure Support**: Uses Garmin's FIT SDK repeat patterns instead of manually creating individual steps:
- `AddIntervals()` method for easy interval creation with automatic repeat structure
- `AddRepeat()` method for custom repeat patterns with child steps
- Proper FIT file generation with parent repeat steps, child steps, and completion steps

**Comprehensive Target Support**: Full support for all Garmin target types including zones and custom ranges:
- Heart Rate zones (1-5) and custom BPM ranges (150-170)
- Speed zones (1-5) and custom speed ranges  
- Power zones (1-5) and custom wattage ranges
- Cadence custom ranges

**Enhanced Builder Methods**: Flexible warm-up and cool-down methods that accept target types:
```csharp
.WarmUp(15, 1, TargetType.Power)   // Power-based warm-up for cycling
.CoolDown(10, 1, TargetType.HeartRate)  // HR-based cool-down
```

**Pre-built Example Workouts**: Ready-to-use workout templates using repeat structures:
- `CreateIntervalWorkoutModel()` - 5x400m track intervals with proper repeat structure
- `CreateCyclingWorkoutModel()` - Power-based cycling intervals with 3x Build/Recovery pattern
- `CreateTempoRunModel()` - 20-minute tempo run

## Implementation Details

The library uses proper Garmin FIT SDK repeat patterns:
- **Repeat Steps**: Parent steps with `RepeatUntilStepsCmplt` duration type
- **Child Steps**: Interval and recovery steps contained within repeat structure  
- **Completion Steps**: Define how many times to repeat the pattern

This approach is more efficient and follows Garmin's recommended practices compared to manually creating individual interval steps.

## Project Structure

The solution file has been moved to the `src/` folder for better organization, with all projects properly referenced.

## Documentation

The README includes comprehensive examples covering:
- Basic workout patterns (warm up, main set, cool down) using `AddTimeStep`
- Interval workouts using repeat structures with explicit option objects
- Fartlek workouts with mixed interval patterns
- Custom repeat patterns and advanced usage
- Complete API documentation with real-world examples

## Testing

The library includes comprehensive test coverage with 23 unit tests covering:
- Model functionality and validation
- Fluent builder pattern behavior including new repeat methods
- File generation capabilities with repeat structure support
- All example workout scenarios using repeat patterns
- Custom target range functionality
- Edge cases and error handling

All tests pass and the library builds without warnings on .NET 8.

Fixes #1.
